Morfometria “tradicional”

Neste tutorial iremos usar o conjunto de dados “Iris”

## Carregando os pacotes que vamos utilizar

library(ade4)
library(MASS)
library(Momocs)
library(scales)
library(ggplot2)

## Importando os dados 

read.table("Iris.txt", sep="\t", header = T) -> iris

Univariada

Histograms

### Vamos dividir o plot em 4 (2 linhas x 2 colunas)

par(mfrow=c(2,2))

### Plotar os histogramas das variáveis

hist(iris$Sepal.Length, main = "Sepal", xlab="length")
hist(iris$Sepal.Width, main = "Sepal", xlab="width")
hist(iris$Petal.Length, main = "Petal", xlab="length")
hist(iris$Petal.Width, main = "Petal", xlab="width")

Boxplots

### Vamos dividir o plot em 4 (2 linhas x 2 colunas)

par(mfrow=c(2,2))

### Plotar os boxplots das variáveis

boxplot(iris$Sepal.Length ~ iris$Species, main="Sepal (l)")
boxplot(iris$Sepal.Width ~ iris$Species, main="Sepal (w)")
boxplot(iris$Petal.Length ~ iris$Species, main="Petal (l)")
boxplot(iris$Petal.Width ~ iris$Species, main="Petal (w)")

Bivariada

Plots

### Plotar as medidas das petalas

plot(iris$Petal.Length, iris$Petal.Width)

### Diferenciar cada uma das especies

cols <- c("red", "blue", "yellow")
pchs <- c(21, 22, 24)

plot(iris$Petal.Length, iris$Petal.Width, bg=cols[iris$Species], pch=pchs[iris$Species], xlab="length", ylab="width", main="Petal")

### Incluir uma legenda

legend("topleft", legend=levels(iris$Species), pch=pchs, pt.bg=cols, box.col=NA)
box()

Análise de outlines

Elliptical fourier analysis

### Diretorio onde estao as outlines

setwd("~/Post-doc-Unicamp/Bioinformatica/Aulas/3 - imageJ/binaries")

### Importar as imagens

list.files(pattern=".jpg") -> jpg.files
import_jpg(jpg.files) -> images
## Extracting 9.jpg outlines...
## [ 1 / 9 ]  sp1.jpg
## [ 2 / 9 ]  sp10.jpg

## [ 4 / 9 ]  sp3.jpg
## [ 5 / 9 ]  sp4.jpg
## [ 6 / 9 ]  sp5.jpg
## [ 7 / 9 ]  sp6.jpg
## [ 8 / 9 ]  sp7.jpg
## [ 9 / 9 ]  sp8.jpg
## Done in 0.8 secs
### Criar um "grupo" (neste caso aletório, mas poderia ser spp, clado, etc..)

LETTERS[1:3][sample(1:3, length(jpg.files), replace=T)] -> facs
as.factor(facs) -> facs

cols[facs] -> cols.clade

######################################
## Coo  ###
######################################

Out(images, fac=facs) -> coo
## Warning: Installed Rcpp (0.12.18) different from Rcpp used to build dplyr (0.12.11).
## Please reinstall dplyr to avoid random crashes or undefined behavior.
panel(coo, cols = 0, borders = 1)

coo_smooth(coo, 100) -> coo
coo_scale(coo, 100) -> coo
coo_center(coo) -> coo

panel(coo, cols=cols.clade, borders=1, names=facs)

######################################
### Efourier and PCA ###
######################################

fouriers <- efourier(coo, nb.h=32, smooth.it=1000, norm=F, start=F)
pcaOut <- PCA(fouriers)
summary(pcaOut)
## Importance of components%s:
##                           PC1    PC2     PC3     PC4     PC5     PC6
## Standard deviation     0.2642 0.1057 0.06652 0.03435 0.02139 0.01133

## Cumulative Proportion  0.8002 0.9283 0.97908 0.99261 0.99785 0.99932
##                             PC7      PC8       PC9
## Standard deviation     0.006934 0.003289 1.614e-17
## Proportion of Variance 0.000550 0.000120 0.000e+00
## Cumulative Proportion  0.999880 1.000000 1.000e+00
######################################
### PC comps reconstruction ###
######################################

PCcontrib(pcaOut) -> pcont

pcont$gg -> pcont

pcont + theme_minimal() + theme(axis.text=element_text(colour="white"), axis.ticks=element_line(colour="white")) + geom_polygon(fill="white", col="black")

######################################
### Shape medio ###
######################################

### O shape médio de todas as pétalas

mshapes(fouriers) -> shape.m.all
## no 'fac' provided, returns meanshape
coo_plot(shape.m.all, col="gray80")

### O shape médio por spp.

mshapes(fouriers, facs) -> shape.m.spp
panel(Opn(shape.m.spp$shp), names=T)

### Testes disponivers, e.g. MANOVA

######################################
### Morphospace
######################################

plot(pcaOut, pos.shp="range")

plot(pcaOut, pos.shp="xy", size.shp=0.8, labelspoints = T)

### Para exportar as coordenadas

pcaOut$x -> coords.p

write.table(coords.p, "PCA_petal_coordinates.txt")
